T Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> ‘land o</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">wners’, and it would be impossible to introduce a taxation of land which would n</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ot negatively affect </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">such </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">agricultural interests</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">  At worst, a taxation of land value could result in a negative equity situation for farm businesses.  In a sector where the re</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">turns on farming are weak and volatile, NFU Scotland considers that this course of action would not be in the best interests of the industry</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p></div></body></html>